Background

This assignment will make use of an external data set, i.e.a data set that you have to upload to R yourself. We will do this using the readr package, which is part of the core tidyverse and assists in reading/writing files. You will be working with a file called "sparrows.csv". You will see this file is available already in this project in the Files pane in RStudio. If you click on this file name, it will appear in the Editor pane - this is a comma-separated file (CSV, comma-separated values), meaning each column of data is separated by a comma. Another way to say this is that the file is comma-delimited. It is also very common to see tab-delimited files (TSV) in data science.

Data in this file was collected in 1898 by Hermon Bumpus, an American biologist working at Brown University. Immediately following a bad winter storm, he collected 136 English house sparrows (some alive, some dead), Passer domesticus, and brought them indoors. Of these birds, 64 had died during the storm, but 72 recovered and survived. Bumpus measured the birds physical traits and recorded them for future generations of data science students.

Reading CSV files and defining factors

We use the function read_csv from the package readr to read in CSV files. When using functions from specific packages, it is often safer to write them in the format package::function(), i.e. readr::read_csv(), just in case there is another function named readr() also floating around in the R environment. It is not likely this will happen to you at this stage of your data sciencing, but it doesnt hurt to get in the habit.

We can read in the file as follows:

## save the data frame, automatically made into a TIBBLE by readr,  into the variable `sparrows`
## readr tells us about all the columns it reads in!!
sparrows <- read_csv("data/sparrows.csv") ## RELATIVE PATH to the dataset
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   Sex = col_character(),
##   Age = col_character(),
##   Survival = col_character(),
##   Length = col_double(),
##   Wingspread = col_double(),
##   Weight = col_double(),
##   Skull_Length = col_double(),
##   Humerus_Length = col_double(),
##   Femur_Length = col_double(),
##   Tarsus_Length = col_double(),
##   Sternum_Length = col_double(),
##   Skull_Width = col_double()
## )

readr has made some very educated guesses as to what type of variable each column stores - it has found three character columns, and nine double columns. Doubles can be thought of numbers with decimals, as opposed to integers - we therefore know these columns contain continuous quantitative data! (Note: it is possible to specify the column types to readr, but thats for another day.)

Lets examine the actual values further:

## Examine the data
#head showed the top 6 of the data
head(sparrows)
## # A tibble: 6 x 12
##   Sex   Age   Survival Length Wingspread Weight Skull_Length Humerus_Length
##   <chr> <chr> <chr>     <dbl>      <dbl>  <dbl>        <dbl>          <dbl>
## 1 Male  Adult Alive       154        241   24.5         31.2           17.4
## 2 Male  Adult Alive       160        252   26.9         30.8           18.7
## 3 Male  Adult Alive       155        243   26.9         30.6           18.6
## 4 Male  Adult Alive       154        245   24.3         31.7           18.8
## 5 Male  Adult Alive       156        247   24.1         31.5           18.2
## 6 Male  Adult Alive       161        253   26.5         31.8           19.8
## #  with 4 more variables: Femur_Length <dbl>, Tarsus_Length <dbl>,
## #   Sternum_Length <dbl>, Skull_Width <dbl>

From the head(sparrows) output, we see that those three character columns appear to contain categories of a categorical variable. In R, we use the data type factor to represent categorical variables, and we call the categories levels. But, R doesnt seem to think that these columns are factors - it thinks they are characters - plain old works with nothing interesting linking them.

In fact, readr assumes that NOTHING is a factor, so we have the full power to determine which variables are factors, and what the order of the categories should be. In R, we call the categories of a factor its levels. While factors are very meaningful, they can be frustrating to work with. Trust me.

The base R version of the read_csv function is read.csv and assumes the opposite - that all characters are factors. This problem notoriously causes everyone a lot of major headaches because factors are very difficult to work with.

Lets therefore begin to convert these columns into factors:

# Convert Sex to a factor 
sparrows$Sex <- factor(sparrows$Sex)

# If we run head() again, we'll see the successful change
head(sparrows)
## # A tibble: 6 x 12
##   Sex   Age   Survival Length Wingspread Weight Skull_Length Humerus_Length
##   <fct> <chr> <chr>     <dbl>      <dbl>  <dbl>        <dbl>          <dbl>
## 1 Male  Adult Alive       154        241   24.5         31.2           17.4
## 2 Male  Adult Alive       160        252   26.9         30.8           18.7
## 3 Male  Adult Alive       155        243   26.9         30.6           18.6
## 4 Male  Adult Alive       154        245   24.3         31.7           18.8
## 5 Male  Adult Alive       156        247   24.1         31.5           18.2
## 6 Male  Adult Alive       161        253   26.5         31.8           19.8
## #  with 4 more variables: Femur_Length <dbl>, Tarsus_Length <dbl>,
## #   Sternum_Length <dbl>, Skull_Width <dbl>
# The levels function tells us the categories in the variable:
levels(sparrows$Sex)
## [1] "Female" "Male"

By definition, levels are ordered, and if no order is specified, R defaults to alphabetical order. To re-order a factor, simply refine the levels with your preferred order of the categories, for example:

# Make the order Male, Female. 
levels(sparrows$Sex) <- c("Male", "Female")

# Print it out to see
print(levels(sparrows$Sex))
## [1] "Male"   "Female"

This can also all be done at once with the single command below.

# Convert to factor and order levels as desired at once
#It is a one line of code to convert the order levels
sparrows$Sex <- factor(sparrows$Sex, levels=c("Male", "Female"))

Question 2

You may have noticed in Question #1, Alive was automatically plotted before Dead. What if we wanted Dead before Alive on the X-axis? Wed have to re-factor the column!. For this question, do the following:

  • Use your new factor skills to convert both Survival and Age to factors. For Survival, set the order to be be (1) Dead, (2) Alive. for Age, the order should be (1) Young, (2) Adult.
    • In total, this should be two lines of code only (one line for each variable) - in a single line, you should set the variable as a factor AND define its levels.
    • Confirm you are correct by printing the LEVELS of each column
  • Then, make a new barplot visualizing Survival with your re-factored variable to see how the X-axis order changed.
## Fill in your code to re-factor and plot here
# the refactor Survival 
sparrows$Survival <- factor(sparrows$Survival, 
                            levels =c("Dead", "Alive"))
#print the Survival factor to see if it worked
print(levels(sparrows$Survival))
## [1] "Dead"  "Alive"
#The barplot of the new re-factor Survival 
ggplot(sparrows, aes(x=Survival))+
  geom_bar(fill="coral")

#The refactor Age 
sparrows$Age <- factor(sparrows$Age, 
                       levels =c("Young", "Adult"))
#print the Age factr to see if it worked 
print(levels(sparrows$Age))
## [1] "Young" "Adult"
Question 3

We will now look at the relationship between two categorical variables using a grouped bar plot. Visualize the distribution of Survival using a bar plot as before, but now color (in this case, fill) the bars by Age. There are two ways these bars can be represented: stacked (this will happen by DEFAULT when you add the fill) or dodged (add the argument position = "dodge" to geom_bar()).

Make one of each type of barplot, and in the space below, answer whether males or females where more likely to survive. Write an additional 1-2 sentences describing which visualization choice makes it easier to answer this question.

## Fill in your code here for the STACKED barplot.
ggplot(sparrows, aes(x=Survival))+
  #It will fill the bars based on the age
  geom_bar(aes(fill=Age)) +
  labs(x="Survival", y="count")-> plot1
## Fill in your code here for the DODGED barplot.
ggplot(sparrows, aes(x=Survival, fill=Age))+
  #The position will make the bars right next to each other 
geom_bar(position="dodge") +
  labs(x="Survival", y="count") -> plot2

The dodge the graph will show it better to say which one is going to survival better.

#The x axis is the Skull Width

  #the density plot filling in the colors with the survival.

Question 6

We will now learn to make a faceted plot, which splits your figure into a row or grid of panels highlighting different subsets of the data. Our goal is to re-make the density plot from Question 5, but faceting by sex: This means there will be one plot for Males and one plot for Females (ordered by factor level!!). There are two functions that can accomplish this: facet_wrap() and facet_grid(); the latter is most useful for faceting multiple variables.

  • Consider this simple example of visualizing iris sepal lengths faceted by Species, using the function facet_wrap():

    ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_density() +
  facet_wrap(~Species) ## the tilde!! so important!! Pronounced as "across" or "by", as in: facet across species, or facet by species

Now, redo your plot from Question 5 so that it is faceted by Sex. In the space below, write 2-4 sentences about whether considering sex separately when plotting helped you to understand trends in the data. What trends do you now see that you didnt see before, if any? What trends are new?

### code for faceted plot goes here
    
# the density plot adding facet_wrap(~Sex)    
ggplot(sparrows, aes(x=Skull_Width))+
#the density plot filling in the colors with the survival. 
#The alpha will make the colors transparent
geom_density(aes(fill=Survival), alpha=0.6) +
  facet_wrap(~Sex) +
#fixs the ladels
labs(x="Skull Width", y="Density") +
   #It will fill in the colors
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("azure4", "aquamarine"))

The graph is differnet in the data. It is eaier to see the Skull Width places a role in Sex. There are more females that dead.

Question 7

Make a jitter plot of Weight across Sex, colored by Age. Before you plot, think carefully about what belongs on X vs Y axis. For this task, you should choose your own colors, ensure the jitter width makes the plot readable, AND place the legend at the BOTTOM of the plot.

#jitter plot with the values Sex, weight and colored by Age
ggplot(sparrows, aes(x=Sex, y=Weight, color=Age)) +

Question 8

Make a second jitter plot of Weight across Sex, except this time color all points according to the birds Length. Again, choose your own colors, ensure an appropriate jitter width, place the legend at the bottom, and ensuring the color scheme is appropriate for the type of variable you are mapping to color which is now a CONTINUOUS variable:

  • When specifying discrete color scales, we use scale_color_manual() (or its _fill_ equivalent)
  • When specifying continuous color scales, we often use one of two functions:
    • scale_color_gradient() (or again its _fill_ equivalent). There is also a function called scale_color_continuous(), which just takes you back to the gradient function anyways.
    • scale_color_distiller(), which provides you access to RColorBrewer palettes.

Get started writing your answer by using the code scale_color_distiller(palette = "Reds") and customize to your liking from there.

### code for jitter plot colored by length goes here

#jitter plot with the values Sex, weight and colored by Age
ggplot(sparrows, aes(x=Sex, y=Weight, color=Skull_Length)) +
  #jitter plot function with a width
  geom_jitter(width = 0.25) +
  scale_color_distiller(palette = "Spectral")

## Scatterplot + line of best fit goes here, with color in ggplot
ggplot(sparrows, aes(x=Skull_Length, y=Skull_Width, color=Sex)) +
  geom_point() + 
  #adding regression line
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  #cleaning up the axis
  labs(x="Skull Length", y="Skull Width") +
  #adding different color
  scale_color_manual(values = c("red", "blue"))

Question 14

Lets learn one more useful geom: geom_text(). Yet again, re-create the same scatterplot but replace geom_point() with geom_text(). This will write some text label rather than drawing points, so we need to tell ggplot what the label is (look up the docs! you can do it!).

Note: neither of these plots is particularly good. But, they do teach how to use geom_text()!

Do this task in two ways:

  • Make all labels the letter B for bird
  • Make all labels the Age of that bird (hint: This is an aesthetic mapping!).
### Scatterplot with points all labeled "B" goes here

#graph + data + axis + color
ggplot(sparrows, aes(x=Skull_Length, y=Skull_Width, color=Sex)) +
  #using the geom_text to make the points into B
  geom_text(label="B") +
  #clean up the axis
  labs(x="Skull Length", y="Skull Width") +
  #changing the colors of the dots
  scale_color_manual(values = c("dodgerblue4", "gold"))

## Scatterplot with points labeled according to age goes here

ggplot(sparrows, aes(x=Skull_Length, y=Skull_Width, color=Sex)) +
# using aesthetic mapping to label with the Age factor
  geom_text(aes(label=Age))+
  #clean up the axis
  labs(x="Skull Length", y="Skull Width") +
  #changing the colors of the dots
  scale_color_manual(values = c("mediumspringgreen", "honeydew4"))

Question 15

We can also learn to change how points are displayed: by default they are dots that can be colored but not filled. It turns out there are many types of shapes that R accepts. The default shape in ggplot is 19. Importantly, point types 21-25 can BOTH be colored (eg black outline) and filled (eg the blue fill).

R point options

Practice specifying two new types of shapes, one that CAN NOT be filled and one that CAN BE filled, in a scatterplot of Skull Width vs Skull Length below. Specify your shape like this: geom_point(shape=...) where ... is the number shape.

### Scatterplot with type of point either 21,22,23,24,25. Specify a color AND a fill (not aesthetic - just straight up color/fill the points)

#Using the plot3 from question 10, it has a shape 25, and fill with Skull Length and in the darkred color
plot3 + geom_point(shape=25,fill="Skull_Length", color="darkred")

### Scatterplot with type of point NOT 21,22,23,24,25. Specify a color (not aesthetic - just straight up color the points)

#Using the plot3 from question 10, it has a shape 11 and color with a black star
plot3 + geom_point(shape=11, color="black")
